04759nam a22006975i 9781501718748DE-B159720230103011142.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230103t20182008nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97815017187487 a10.7591/97815017187482doi  a(DE-B1597)514886  a(OCoLC)1083581550  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aJC71b.R66 2008eb 7aPHI0020002bisacsh04a321/.072231 aRoochnik, David, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBeautiful City :bThe Dialectical Character of Plato's "Republic" /cDavid Roochnik. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2018] 4c©2008  a1 online resource (176 p.) :b3 charts/graphs, 1 line drawing  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tPrologue -- tCHAPTER ONE. The Arithmetical -- tI. TRIPARTITE CITY, TRIPARTITE SOUL -- t2. “THE ONE, THE TWO, AND THE THREE” -- t3. THE ARITHMETICAL CHARACTER OF KALLIPOLIS -- tCHAPTER TWO. Eros -- tI. INTIMATIONS OF EROS -- t2. THE THREE WAVES -- t3. KALLIPOLIS VERSUS THE REPUBLIC -- tCHAPTER THREE. Democracy, Psychology, Poetry -- tI. DEMOCRACY -- t2. NARRATIVE PSYCHOLOGY -- t3. PSYCHOLOGICAL NARRATIVE -- tAPPENDIX. The Meaning of “Dialectical” -- tI. THE TECHNICAL MEANING OF “DIALECTIC” -- t2. THE NONTECHNICAL MEANING OF “DIALECTIC” -- t3· DIALECTIC IN THE REPUBLIC -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aTo the vast literature on Plato's Republic comes a new interpretation. In Beautiful City, David Roochnik argues convincingly that Plato's masterpiece is misunderstood by modern readers. The work must, he explains, be read dialectically, its parts understood as forming a unified whole. Approached in this way, the text no longer appears to defend an authoritarian and monolithic political system, but rather supplies a qualified defense of democracy and the values of diversity.Writing in clear and straightforward prose, Roochnik demonstrates how Plato's treatment of the city and the soul evolves throughout the dialogue and can be appreciated only by considering the Republic in its entirety. He shows that the views expressed in the early parts of the text do not represent Plato's final judgment on these subjects but are in fact dialectical "moments" intended to be both partial and provisional. Books 5-7 of the Republic are, he maintains, meant to revise and improve upon books 2-4. Similarly, he sees the usually neglected books 8-10 as advancing beyond the thoughts presented in the previous books. Paying particular attention to these later books, Roochnik details, for instance, how the stories of the "mistaken" regimes, which are often seen as unimportant, are actually crucial in Plato's account of the soul.Beautiful City is certain to be controversial, as the author's insights and opinions will engage and challenge philosophers, classicists, and political theorists.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 03. Jan 2023) 4aHistory. 4aPhilosophy. 7aPHILOSOPHY / History & Surveys / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013z978311053615708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG and UP eBook Package 2000-2015z97831106387210 cprintz978080147453840uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150171874840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501718748423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501718748/original  a978-3-11-053615-7  Cornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-063872-1  DG and UP eBook Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_CL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_CL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyt